  "prompt": "Do anti-money laundering regulations exist?",
  "response": "Yes, anti-money laundering (AML) regulations exist in many countries and at international levels. These regulations are designed to prevent criminals from disguising illegally obtained funds as legitimate income. Key examples include:\n\n1. United States: Bank Secrecy Act (BSA) and USA PATRIOT Act\n2. European Union: Anti-Money Laundering Directives\n3. Financial Action Task Force (FATF) international standards\n4. United Kingdom: Proceeds of Crime Act\n5. International monetary and banking regulations\n\nThese regulations typically require financial institutions to:\n- Verify customer identities\n- Monitor suspicious transactions\n- Report large cash transactions\n- Maintain transaction records\n- Implement compliance programs\n\nPenalties for non-compliance can include significant fines and criminal charges.",
